---
slug: order-judgment-appeal
title: Order and Judgment on Appeal
description: This skill guides drafting appellate court orders and judgments, focusing on the procedural history, issues, standard of review, analysis, disposition, remand, costs, mandate, and signatures. It covers key pleading document types within appellate practice areas to assist legal drafters in producing structured and clear appellate decisions.
practice_areas: Appellate, Litigation
legal_context: Appellate Procedure, Court Decisions
document_types: Pleading, Order, Judgment
skill_modes: Drafting

# Purpose
Provide a structured process and templates to draft clear, comprehensive appellate orders and judgments.

# Prerequisites
1. Familiarity with appellate procedure and terminology.
2. Understanding of the underlying trial issues and record.
3. Access to relevant statutes and case law for standard of review.
4. Knowledge of court-specific formatting and filing requirements.

# Structure / Process

| Section              | Description                                                    |
|----------------------|----------------------------------------------------------------|
| Caption              | Court, parties, case number, and appeal designation.           |
| Procedural History   | Summary of prior proceedings and relevant timeline.            |
| Issues                | Clearly defined appellate issues presented for review.         |
| Standard of Review    | Legal standards guiding the appellate court’s review.          |
| Analysis              | Reasoned evaluation applying law to facts and arguments.       |
| Disposition           | The court’s decision on each issue (affirm, reverse, etc.).      |
| Remand                | Instructions for further proceedings if necessary.             |
| Costs                 | Allocation of fees and costs between parties.                   |
| Mandate               | Formal court order effectuating the judgment.                   |
| Signatures            | Authorized signatures from judges or clerks.                    |

# Guidelines
- Use clear, concise language avoiding legal jargon where possible.
- Clearly separate each section with appropriate headings.
- Keep analysis focused on legal reasoning, citing legal authorities as needed [VERIFY].
- Maintain consistent formatting aligned with court rules.
- Use templates for uniformity and efficiency.
- Avoid nested bullet points to enhance readability.
- Include a checklist to ensure all components are addressed.
- Ensure the document complies with jurisdiction-specific requirements.
- Use flat lists in each section for clarity.
- Verify citations and procedural facts before finalizing drafts.

# Templates

## Caption
Court of [Name]  
Case No. [Number]  
[Appellant] v. [Appellee]  
Order and Judgment on Appeal

## Procedural History
A brief narrative summarizing the trial court proceedings, motions, and appeals leading to the current appeal.

## Issues
1. Whether the trial court erred in [specific ruling].
2. Whether the evidence supports the judgment.

## Standard of Review
The appellate court reviews [factual findings for clear error/legal conclusions de novo] [VERIFY depending on jurisdiction].

## Analysis
Detailed reasoning applying legal standards to the facts, addressing each issue in turn.

## Disposition
The judgment is [affirmed/reversed/remanded] in part and [affirmed/reversed/remanded] in part.

## Remand
If applicable, instructions to the lower court for further proceedings on specified issues.

## Costs
Costs [are/are not] awarded to [party], subject to court rules.

## Mandate
The court issues its mandate directing the clerk to enter judgment consistent with this order.

## Signatures
[Judge Names], [Titles]  
Dated: [Date]

# Checklist
- [ ] Caption completed with accurate case information  
- [ ] Procedural history concise and accurate  
- [ ] Issues clearly identified and numbered  
- [ ] Standard of review stated and appropriate  
- [ ] Analysis addresses each issue with cited authority  
- [ ] Disposition clearly states outcome per issue  
- [ ] Remand instructions (if any) are clear  
- [ ] Costs allocation specified  
- [ ] Mandate language formal and complete  
- [ ] Signatures include all required parties  
- [ ] Formatting aligns with court rules  
- [ ] No nested bullets; flat lists used throughout  
- [ ] Citations and procedural facts verified [VERIFY]  

